<TITLE> Germany agrees rules on ending coal mining by 2018 </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BERLIN, Aug 8 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The German government on Wednesday approved rules to regulate the gradual phasing out of coal mining by 2018, marking the beginning of the end of the 200-year-old industry in Europe's biggest economy. The rules need approval by the lower house, or Bundestag, and the Bundesrat upper house where the 16 states are represented, but this is expected to be a formality as the government has a clear majority in both houses. The volume of coal subsidies for the phase out between 2009 and 2018 will be as high as 21.6 billion euros ($29.8 billion), 15.6 billion of which will come from the federal government, according to the Economy Ministry. Earlier this year, the government agreed the rules with the states, labour unions and industrial conglomerate RAG. RAG, which is planning to list on the stock market, retains power, chemicals and real estate units. Germany has eight mines in use, seven in the state of North-Rhine Westphalia (NRW) and one in Saarland. Around 35,000 workers are employed in the sector. The rules agreed on Wednesday contain a clause which would allow the phaseout to be reversed in the event of power shortages or exorbitantly higher prices for other energy for
